    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''On Easter, Symbolism and the Exuberance of Spring'' (April 4), I was perplexed by Nancy Harmon Jenkins's opinion that mageiritsa is ''quite impossible to prepare in the United States, where there is almost no access to baby lamb, let alone to its innards or to wild fennel greens.'' Almost every butcher in Astoria can order baby lamb and sell any amount of innards necessary for the traditional Greek dish. Also, many greengrocers in the area carry wild fennel. The dish is made every year by Americans of Greek heritage.</p>
        <p>LISA DELANGE  Jackson Heights, Queens</p>
